[Settings](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/settings.html)

Summary[Source](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/src/h2/lib.rs.html#1-162)
Expand description
An asynchronous, HTTP/2 server and client implementation.
This library implements the [HTTP/2](https://http2.github.io/) specification. The implementation is asynchronous, using [futures](https://docs.rs/futures/) as the basis for the API. The implementation is also decoupled from TCP or TLS details. The user must handle ALPN and HTTP/1.1 upgrades themselves.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#getting-started)Getting started
Add the following to your `Cargo.toml` file:
```
[dependencies]
h2 = "0.4"
```

## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#layout-1)Layout
The crate is split into [`client`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/index.html) and [`server`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/index.html) modules. Types that are common to both clients and servers are located at the root of the crate.
See module level documentation for more details on how to use `h2`.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#handshake)Handshake
Both the client and the server require a connection to already be in a state ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake. This library does not provide facilities to do this.
There are three ways to reach an appropriate state to start the HTTP/2 handshake.
  * Opening an HTTP/1.1 connection and performing an [upgrade](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Protocol_upgrade_mechanism).
  * Opening a connection with TLS and use ALPN to negotiate the protocol.
  * Open a connection with prior knowledge, i.e. both the client and the server assume that the connection is immediately ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake once opened.


Once the connection is ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake, it can be passed to [`server::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/fn.handshake.html) or [`client::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/fn.handshake.html). At this point, the library will start the handshake process, which consists of:
  * The client sends the connection preface (a predefined sequence of 24 octets).
  * Both the client and the server sending a SETTINGS frame.


See the [Starting HTTP/2](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#starting) in the specification for more details.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#flow-control)Flow control
[Flow control](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#FlowControl) is a fundamental feature of HTTP/2. The `h2` library exposes flow control to the user.
An HTTP/2 client or server may not send unlimited data to the peer. When a stream is initiated, both the client and the server are provided with an initial window size for that stream. A window size is the number of bytes the endpoint can send to the peer. At any point in time, the peer may increase this window size by sending a `WINDOW_UPDATE` frame. Once a client or server has sent data filling the window for a stream, no further data may be sent on that stream until the peer increases the window.
There is also a **connection level** window governing data sent across all streams.
Managing flow control for inbound data is done through [`FlowControl`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.FlowControl.html). Managing flow control for outbound data is done through [`SendStream`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.SendStream.html). See the struct level documentation for those two types for more details.
## Modules[§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#modules)

[client](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/index.html "mod h2::client")
    Client implementation of the HTTP/2 protocol.

[ext](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/ext/index.html "mod h2::ext")
    Extensions specific to the HTTP/2 protocol.

[server](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/index.html "mod h2::server")
    Server implementation of the HTTP/2 protocol.
## Structs[§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#structs)

[Error](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Error.html "struct h2::Error")
    Represents HTTP/2 operation errors.

[FlowControl](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.FlowControl.html "struct h2::FlowControl")
    A handle to release window capacity to a remote stream.

[Ping](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Ping.html "struct h2::Ping")
    Sent via [`PingPong`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html) to send a PING frame to a peer.

[PingPong](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html "struct h2::PingPong")
    A handle to send and receive PING frames with the peer.

[Pong](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Pong.html "struct h2::Pong")
    Received via [`PingPong`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html) when a peer acknowledges a [`Ping`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Ping.html).

[Reason](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Reason.html "struct h2::Reason")
    HTTP/2 error codes.

[RecvStream](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.RecvStream.html "struct h2::RecvStream")
    Receives the body stream and trailers from the remote peer.

[SendStream](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.SendStream.html "struct h2::SendStream")
    Sends the body stream and trailers to the remote peer.

[StreamId](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.StreamId.html "struct h2::StreamId")
    A stream identifier, as described in [Section 5.1.1](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7540#section-5.1.1) of RFC 7540.

# H2
A Tokio aware, HTTP/2 client & server implementation for Rust.
[![License: MIT](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-MIT-blue.svg)](https://opensource.org/licenses/MIT) [![Crates.io](https://img.shields.io/crates/v/h2.svg)](https://crates.io/crates/h2) [![Documentation](https://img.gs/czjpqfbdkz/full/https://docs.rs/h2/badge.svg)](https://docs.rs/h2)
More information about this crate can be found in the [crate documentation](https://docs.rs/h2).
## Features
  * Client and server HTTP/2 implementation.
  * Implements the full HTTP/2 specification.
  * Passes [h2spec](https://github.com/summerwind/h2spec).
  * Focus on performance and correctness.
  * Built on [Tokio](https://tokio.rs).


## Non goals
This crate is intended to only be an implementation of the HTTP/2 specification. It does not handle:
  * Managing TCP connections
  * HTTP 1.0 upgrade
  * TLS
  * Any feature not described by the HTTP/2 specification.


This crate is now used by [hyper](https://github.com/hyperium/hyper), which will provide all of these features.
## Usage
To use ``h2``, first add this to your ``Cargo.toml``:
```
```[``dependencies``]`
`h2 ``=` ``"`0.4`"``
``
```

Next, add this to your crate:
```
``extern` `crate` h2`;`
`use` `h2`::```server`::``Connection`;`
``fn` `main`````(````)``````{`
  ``//` ...`
```}```
`
```

## FAQ
**How does h2 compare to[solicit](https://github.com/mlalic/solicit) or [rust-http2](https://github.com/stepancheg/rust-http2)?**
The h2 library has implemented more of the details of the HTTP/2 specification than any other Rust library. It also passes the [h2spec](https://github.com/summerwind/h2spec) set of tests. The h2 library is rapidly approaching "production ready" quality.
Besides the above, Solicit is built on blocking I/O and does not appear to be actively maintained.
**Is this an embedded Java SQL database engine?**
[No](https://www.h2database.com).

advisory.title: Some AES functions may panic when overflow checking is enabled.
advisory.description:
`ring::aead::quic::HeaderProtectionKey::new_mask()` may panic when overflow
checking is enabled. In the QUIC protocol, an attacker can induce this panic by
sending a specially-crafted packet. Even unintentionally it is likely to occur
in 1 out of every 2**32 packets sent and/or received.

On 64-bit targets operations using `ring::aead::{AES_128_GCM, AES_256_GCM}` may
panic when overflow checking is enabled, when encrypting/decrypting approximately
68,719,476,700 bytes (about 64 gigabytes) of data in a single chunk. Protocols
like TLS and SSH are not affected by this because those protocols break large
amounts of data into small chunks. Similarly, most applications will not
attempt to encrypt/decrypt 64GB of data in one chunk.

Overflow checking is not enabled in release mode by default, but
`RUSTFLAGS="-C overflow-checks"` or `overflow-checks = true` in the Cargo.toml
profile can override this. Overflow checking is usually enabled by default in
debug mode.

advisory.title: rustls network-reachable panic in `Acceptor::accept`
advisory.description:
A bug introduced in rustls 0.23.13 leads to a panic if the received
TLS ClientHello is fragmented.  Only servers that use
`rustls::server::Acceptor::accept()` are affected.

Servers that use `tokio-rustls`'s `LazyConfigAcceptor` API are affected.

Servers that use `tokio-rustls`'s `TlsAcceptor` API are not affected.

Servers that use `rustls-ffi`'s `rustls_acceptor_accept` API are affected.

advisory.title: paste - no longer maintained
advisory.description:
The creator of the crate `paste` has stated in the [`README.md`](https://github.com/dtolnay/paste/blob/master/README.md) 
that this project is not longer maintained as well as archived the repository

advisory.title: Broadcast channel calls clone in parallel, but does not require `Sync`
advisory.description:
The broadcast channel internally calls `clone` on the stored value when
receiving it, and only requires `T:Send`. This means that using the broadcast
channel with values that are `Send` but not `Sync` can trigger unsoundness if
the `clone` implementation makes use of the value being `!Sync`.

Thank you to Austin Bonander for finding and reporting this issue.

# Crate h2Copy item path
[Settings](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/settings.html)
[Help](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/help.html)
Summary[Source](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/src/h2/lib.rs.html#1-162)
Expand description
An asynchronous, HTTP/2 server and client implementation.
This library implements the [HTTP/2](https://http2.github.io/) specification. The implementation is asynchronous, using [futures](https://docs.rs/futures/) as the basis for the API. The implementation is also decoupled from TCP or TLS details. The user must handle ALPN and HTTP/1.1 upgrades themselves.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#getting-started)Getting started
Add the following to your `Cargo.toml` file:
```
[dependencies]
h2 = "0.4"
```

## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#layout-1)Layout
The crate is split into [`client`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/index.html) and [`server`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/index.html) modules. Types that are common to both clients and servers are located at the root of the crate.
See module level documentation for more details on how to use `h2`.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#handshake)Handshake
Both the client and the server require a connection to already be in a state ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake. This library does not provide facilities to do this.
There are three ways to reach an appropriate state to start the HTTP/2 handshake.
  * Opening an HTTP/1.1 connection and performing an [upgrade](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Protocol_upgrade_mechanism).
  * Opening a connection with TLS and use ALPN to negotiate the protocol.
  * Open a connection with prior knowledge, i.e. both the client and the server assume that the connection is immediately ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake once opened.


Once the connection is ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake, it can be passed to [`server::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/fn.handshake.html) or [`client::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/fn.handshake.html). At this point, the library will start the handshake process, which consists of:
  * The client sends the connection preface (a predefined sequence of 24 octets).
  * Both the client and the server sending a SETTINGS frame.


See the [Starting HTTP/2](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#starting) in the specification for more details.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#flow-control)Flow control
[Flow control](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#FlowControl) is a fundamental feature of HTTP/2. The `h2` library exposes flow control to the user.
An HTTP/2 client or server may not send unlimited data to the peer. When a stream is initiated, both the client and the server are provided with an initial window size for that stream. A window size is the number of bytes the endpoint can send to the peer. At any point in time, the peer may increase this window size by sending a `WINDOW_UPDATE` frame. Once a client or server has sent data filling the window for a stream, no further data may be sent on that stream until the peer increases the window.
There is also a **connection level** window governing data sent across all streams.
Managing flow control for inbound data is done through [`FlowControl`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.FlowControl.html). Managing flow control for outbound data is done through [`SendStream`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.SendStream.html). See the struct level documentation for those two types for more details.
## Modules[§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#modules)

[client](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/index.html "mod h2::client")
    Client implementation of the HTTP/2 protocol.

[ext](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/ext/index.html "mod h2::ext")
    Extensions specific to the HTTP/2 protocol.

[server](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/index.html "mod h2::server")
    Server implementation of the HTTP/2 protocol.
## Structs[§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#structs)

[Error](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Error.html "struct h2::Error")
    Represents HTTP/2 operation errors.

[FlowControl](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.FlowControl.html "struct h2::FlowControl")
    A handle to release window capacity to a remote stream.

[Ping](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Ping.html "struct h2::Ping")
    Sent via [`PingPong`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html) to send a PING frame to a peer.

[PingPong](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html "struct h2::PingPong")
    A handle to send and receive PING frames with the peer.

[Pong](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Pong.html "struct h2::Pong")
    Received via [`PingPong`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.PingPong.html) when a peer acknowledges a [`Ping`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Ping.html).

[Reason](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.Reason.html "struct h2::Reason")
    HTTP/2 error codes.

[RecvStream](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.RecvStream.html "struct h2::RecvStream")
    Receives the body stream and trailers from the remote peer.

[SendStream](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.SendStream.html "struct h2::SendStream")
    Sends the body stream and trailers to the remote peer.

[StreamId](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.StreamId.html "struct h2::StreamId")
    A stream identifier, as described in [Section 5.1.1](https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc7540#section-5.1.1) of RFC 7540.

Expand description
An asynchronous, HTTP/2 server and client implementation.
This library implements the [HTTP/2](https://http2.github.io/) specification. The implementation is asynchronous, using [futures](https://docs.rs/futures/) as the basis for the API. The implementation is also decoupled from TCP or TLS details. The user must handle ALPN and HTTP/1.1 upgrades themselves.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#getting-started)Getting started
Add the following to your `Cargo.toml` file:
```
[dependencies]
h2 = "0.4"
```

## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#layout-1)Layout
The crate is split into [`client`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/index.html) and [`server`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/index.html) modules. Types that are common to both clients and servers are located at the root of the crate.
See module level documentation for more details on how to use `h2`.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#handshake)Handshake
Both the client and the server require a connection to already be in a state ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake. This library does not provide facilities to do this.
There are three ways to reach an appropriate state to start the HTTP/2 handshake.
  * Opening an HTTP/1.1 connection and performing an [upgrade](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Protocol_upgrade_mechanism).
  * Opening a connection with TLS and use ALPN to negotiate the protocol.
  * Open a connection with prior knowledge, i.e. both the client and the server assume that the connection is immediately ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake once opened.


Once the connection is ready to start the HTTP/2 handshake, it can be passed to [`server::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/server/fn.handshake.html) or [`client::handshake`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/client/fn.handshake.html). At this point, the library will start the handshake process, which consists of:
  * The client sends the connection preface (a predefined sequence of 24 octets).
  * Both the client and the server sending a SETTINGS frame.


See the [Starting HTTP/2](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#starting) in the specification for more details.
## [§](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/#flow-control)Flow control
[Flow control](http://httpwg.org/specs/rfc7540.html#FlowControl) is a fundamental feature of HTTP/2. The `h2` library exposes flow control to the user.
An HTTP/2 client or server may not send unlimited data to the peer. When a stream is initiated, both the client and the server are provided with an initial window size for that stream. A window size is the number of bytes the endpoint can send to the peer. At any point in time, the peer may increase this window size by sending a `WINDOW_UPDATE` frame. Once a client or server has sent data filling the window for a stream, no further data may be sent on that stream until the peer increases the window.
There is also a **connection level** window governing data sent across all streams.
Managing flow control for inbound data is done through [`FlowControl`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.FlowControl.html). Managing flow control for outbound data is done through [`SendStream`](https://docs.rs/h2/latest/h2/struct.SendStream.html). See the struct level documentation for those two types for more details.

enriched_crate.readme_summary: The `h2` crate is an asynchronous implementation of the HTTP/2 protocol for both clients and servers, built on the `futures` ecosystem. It provides tools for managing HTTP/2 features like flow control, stream handling, and protocol-specific operations (e.g., handshake, ping/pong). The crate is transport-agnostic, requiring users to handle connection setup (e.g., ALPN or HTTP/1.1 upgrades) externally.
enriched_crate.factual_counterfactual:
### Pair 1: Handshake Implementation  
✅ **Factual**: The `h2` crate requires the connection to be in a state ready for the HTTP/2 handshake, but it does not provide facilities for handling ALPN or HTTP/1.1 upgrades; these must be managed externally.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `h2` crate automatically handles ALPN and HTTP/1.1 upgrades to prepare the connection for the HTTP/2 handshake.  

---

### Pair 2: Flow Control  
✅ **Factual**: The `h2` crate provides explicit flow control mechanisms via the `FlowControl` and `SendStream` structs, allowing users to manage both inbound and outbound data window sizes.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `h2` crate does not implement flow control mechanisms, leaving users to manage data transmission limits manually.  

---

### Pair 3: Client and Server Modules  
✅ **Factual**: The `h2` crate is divided into `client` and `server` modules, enabling separate implementations for HTTP/2 client and server functionalities, with shared types located at the root of the crate.  
❌ **Counterfactual**: The `h2` crate combines client and server functionalities into a single module, without separating their implementations.
